# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: non-euclidean-geometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The appearance of work on this geometry in the nineteenth century stimulated the development of non-Euclidean geometry generally, including hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Elliptic geometry has a variety of properties that differ from those of classical Euclidean plane geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] For example, the sum of the interior angles of any triangle is always greater than 180°.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Elliptic geometry may be derived from spherical geometry by identifying antipodal points of the sphere to a single elliptic point.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The elliptic lines correspond to great circles reduced by the identification of antipodal points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] As any two great circles intersect, there are no parallel lines in elliptic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In elliptic geometry, two lines perpendicular to a given line must intersect.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In fact, all perpendiculars to a given line intersect at a single point called the *absolute pole* of that line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Every point corresponds to an *absolute polar line* of which it is the absolute pole.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Any point on this polar line forms an *absolute conjugate pair* with the pole.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Such a pair of points is *orthogonal*, and the distance between them is a *quadrant*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The **distance** between a pair of points is proportional to the angle between their absolute polars.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The name "elliptic" is possibly misleading.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] It does not imply any direct connection with the curve called an ellipse, but only a rather far-fetched analogy.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The elliptic plane is the real projective plane provided with a metric.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Kepler and Desargues used the gnomonic projection to relate a plane σ to points on a hemisphere tangent to it.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] With *O* the center of the hemisphere, a point *P* in σ determines a line *OP* intersecting the hemisphere, and any line *L* ⊂ σ determines a plane *OL* which intersects the hemisphere in half of a great circle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The hemisphere is bounded by a plane through O and parallel to σ.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] No ordinary line of *σ* corresponds to this plane; instead a line at infinity is appended to *σ*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] As any line in this extension of σ corresponds to a plane through *O*, and since any pair of such planes intersects in a line through *O*, one can conclude that any pair of lines in the extension intersect: the point of intersection lies where the plane intersection meets σ or the line at infinity.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Thus the axiom of projective geometry, requiring all pairs of lines in a plane to intersect, is confirmed.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Given *P* and *Q* in *σ*, the **elliptic distance** between them is the measure of the angle *POQ*, usually taken in radians.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Arthur Cayley initiated the study of elliptic geometry when he wrote "On the definition of distance".
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] This venture into abstraction in geometry was followed by Felix Klein and Bernhard Riemann leading to non-Euclidean geometry and Riemannian geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In Euclidean geometry, a figure can be scaled up or scaled down indefinitely, and the resulting figures are similar, i.e., they have the same angles and the same internal proportions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In elliptic geometry, this is not the case.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] For example, in the spherical model we can see that the distance between any two points must be strictly less than half the circumference of the sphere (because antipodal points are identified).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] A line segment therefore cannot be scaled up indefinitely.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] A great deal of Euclidean geometry carries over directly to elliptic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] For example, the first and fourth of Euclid's postulates, that there is a unique line between any two points and that all right angles are equal, hold in elliptic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Postulate 3, that one can construct a circle with any given center and radius, fails if "any radius" is taken to mean "any real number", but holds if it is taken to mean "the length of any given line segment".
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Therefore any result in Euclidean geometry that follows from these three postulates will hold in elliptic geometry, such as proposition 1 from book I of the *Elements*, which states that given any line segment, an equilateral triangle can be constructed with the segment as its base.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Elliptic geometry is also like Euclidean geometry in that space is continuous, homogeneous, isotropic, and without boundaries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Isotropy is guaranteed by the fourth postulate, that all right angles are equal.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] For an example of homogeneity, note that Euclid's proposition I.1 implies that the same equilateral triangle can be constructed at any location, not just in locations that are special in some way.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The lack of boundaries follows from the second postulate, extensibility of a line segment.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] One way in which elliptic geometry differs from Euclidean geometry is that the sum of the interior angles of a triangle is greater than 180 degrees.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In the spherical model, for example, a triangle can be constructed with vertices at the locations where the three positive Cartesian coordinate axes intersect the sphere, and all three of its internal angles are 90 degrees, summing to 270 degrees.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] For sufficiently small triangles, the excess over 180 degrees can be made arbitrarily small.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The Pythagorean theorem fails in elliptic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In the 90°–90°–90° triangle described above, all three sides have the same length, and consequently do not satisfy $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$ .
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The Pythagorean result is recovered in the limit of small triangles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The ratio of a circle's circumference to its area is smaller than in Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In general, area and volume do not scale as the second and third powers of linear dimensions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Elliptic space can be constructed in a way similar to the construction of three-dimensional vector space: with equivalence classes.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] One uses directed arcs on great circles of the sphere.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] As directed line segments are equipollent when they are parallel, of the same length, and similarly oriented, so directed arcs found on great circles are equipollent when they are of the same length, orientation, and great circle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] These relations of equipollence produce 3D vector space and elliptic space, respectively.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Access to elliptic space structure is provided through the vector algebra of William Rowan Hamilton: he envisioned a sphere as a domain of square roots of minus one.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Then Euler's formula $\exp(\theta r)=\cos \theta +r\sin \theta$ (where *r* is on the sphere) represents the great circle in the plane containing 1 and *r*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Opposite points *r* and −*r* correspond to oppositely directed circles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] An arc between θ and φ is equipollent with one between 0 and φ − θ.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In elliptic space, arc length is less than π, so arcs may be parametrized with θ in [0, π) or (−π/2, π/2].
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] For $z=\exp(\theta r),\ z^{*}=\exp(-\theta r)\implies zz^{*}=1.$ It is said that the modulus or norm of *z* is one (Hamilton called it the tensor of z).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] But since *r* ranges over a sphere in 3-space, exp(θ r) ranges over a sphere in 4-space, now called the 3-sphere, as its surface has three dimensions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Hamilton called his algebra quaternions and it quickly became a useful and celebrated tool of mathematics.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Its space of four dimensions is evolved in polar co-ordinates $t\exp(\theta r),$ with *t* in the positive real numbers.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] When doing trigonometry on Earth or the celestial sphere, the sides of the triangles are great circle arcs.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The first success of quaternions was a rendering of spherical trigonometry to algebra.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Hamilton called a quaternion of norm one a versor, and these are the points of elliptic space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] For an arbitrary versor *u*, the distance will be that θ for which cos θ = (*u* + *u*∗)/2 since this is the formula for the scalar part of any quaternion.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Distances between points are the same as between image points of an elliptic motion.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In the case that u and v are quaternion conjugates of one another, the motion is a spatial rotation, and their vector part is the axis of rotation.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In the case *u* = 1 the elliptic motion is called a right *Clifford translation*, or a *parataxy*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The case *v* = 1 corresponds to left Clifford translation.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] They are the right and left Clifford translations of u along an elliptic line through 1.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The *elliptic space* is formed from S3 by identifying antipodal points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Elliptic space has special structures called Clifford parallels and Clifford surfaces.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The versor points of elliptic space are mapped by the Cayley transform to $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ for an alternative representation of the space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The hyperspherical model is the generalization of the spherical model to higher dimensions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The points of *n*-dimensional elliptic space are the pairs of unit vectors (*x*, −*x*) in **R***n*+1, that is, pairs of antipodal points on the surface of the unit ball in (*n* + 1)-dimensional space (the *n*-dimensional hypersphere).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Lines in this model are great circles, i.e., intersections of the hypersphere with flat hypersurfaces of dimension *n* passing through the origin.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] In the projective model of elliptic geometry, the points of *n*-dimensional real projective space are used as points of the model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] This models an abstract elliptic geometry that is also known as projective geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The points of *n*-dimensional projective space can be identified with lines through the origin in (*n* + 1)-dimensional space, and can be represented non-uniquely by nonzero vectors in **R***n*+1, with the understanding that u and λ*u*, for any non-zero scalar λ, represent the same point.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] that is, the distance between two points is the angle between their corresponding lines in **R***n*+1.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The distance formula is homogeneous in each variable, with *d*(λ*u*, μ*v*) = *d*(*u*, *v*) if λ and μ are non-zero scalars, so it does define a distance on the points of projective space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] A notable property of the projective elliptic geometry is that for even dimensions, such as the plane, the geometry is non-orientable.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] It erases the distinction between clockwise and counterclockwise rotation by identifying them.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] A model representing the same space as the hyperspherical model can be obtained by means of stereographic projection.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Let **E***n* represent **R***n* ∪ {∞}, that is, n-dimensional real space extended by a single point at infinity.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] where u and v are any two vectors in **R***n* and $\|\cdot \|$ is the usual Euclidean norm.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] The result is a metric space on **E***n*, which represents the distance along a chord of the corresponding points on the hyperspherical model, to which it maps bijectively by stereographic projection.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Elliptic geometry is obtained from this by identifying the antipodal points u and −*u* / ‖*u*‖2, and taking the distance from v to this pair to be the minimum of the distances from v to each of these two points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Because spherical elliptic geometry can be modeled as, for example, a spherical subspace of a Euclidean space, it follows that if Euclidean geometry is self-consistent, so is spherical elliptic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Therefore it is not possible to prove the parallel postulate based on the other four postulates of Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] Tarski proved that elementary Euclidean geometry is complete: there is an algorithm which, for every proposition, can show it to be either true or false.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/elliptic-geometry] (This does not violate Gödel's theorem, because Euclidean geometry cannot describe a sufficient amount of arithmetic for the theorem to apply.) It therefore follows that elementary elliptic geometry is also self-consistent and complete.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The Gaussian curvature can also be negative, as in the case of a hyperboloid or the inside of a torus.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] This is the content of the *Theorema Egregium*, published by Gauss in 1827.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] At any point on a surface, we can find a normal vector that is at right angles to the surface; planes containing the normal vector are called *normal planes*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The intersection of a normal plane and the surface will form a curve called a *normal section* and the curvature of this curve is the *normal curvature*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] For most points on most “smooth” surfaces, different normal sections will have different curvatures; the maximum and minimum values of these are called the principal curvatures, call these *κ*1, *κ*2.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The **Gaussian curvature** is the product of the two principal curvatures *Κ* = *κ*1*κ*2.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The sign of the Gaussian curvature can be used to characterise the surface.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Most surfaces will contain regions of positive Gaussian curvature (elliptical points) and regions of negative Gaussian curvature separated by a curve of points with zero Gaussian curvature called a parabolic line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] When a surface has a constant zero Gaussian curvature, then it is a developable surface and the geometry of the surface is Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] When a surface has a constant positive Gaussian curvature, then the geometry of the surface is spherical geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Spheres and patches of spheres have this geometry, but there exist other examples as well, such as the lemon / American football.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] When a surface has a constant negative Gaussian curvature, then it is a pseudospherical surface and the geometry of the surface is hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The two principal curvatures at a given point of a surface are the eigenvalues of the shape operator at the point.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] They measure how the surface bends by different amounts in different directions from that point.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] We represent the surface by the implicit function theorem as the graph of a function, f, of two variables, in such a way that the point p is a critical point, that is, the gradient of f vanishes (this can always be attained by a suitable rigid motion).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Then the Gaussian curvature of the surface at p is the determinant of the 2 x 2 Hessian matrix of f (being the product of the eigenvalues of the Hessian).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] (Recall that the Hessian is a symmetric matrix of second derivatives, which in Euclidean space is diagonalizable via the special case of the spectral theorem restricted to when H is equivalent to its conjugate transpose, i.e.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] H is real) This definition allows one immediately to grasp the distinction between a cup/cap versus a saddle point.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] At a point **p** on a regular surface in **R**3, the Gaussian curvature is also given by $K(\mathbf {p} )=\det S(\mathbf {p} ),$ where S is the shape operator.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] A useful formula for the Gaussian curvature is Liouville's equation in terms of the Laplacian in isothermal coordinates.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The surface integral of the Gaussian curvature over some region of a surface is called the **total curvature**.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The total curvature of a geodesic triangle equals the deviation of the sum of its angles from π.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The sum of the angles of a triangle on a surface of positive curvature will exceed π, while the sum of the angles of a triangle on a surface of negative curvature will be less than π.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] On a surface of zero curvature, such as the Euclidean plane, the angles will sum to precisely π radians. $\sum _{i=1}^{3}\theta _{i}=\pi +\iint _{T}K\,dA.$ A more general result is the Gauss–Bonnet theorem.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Gauss's *Theorema egregium* (Latin: "remarkable theorem") states that Gaussian curvature of a surface can be determined from the measurements of length on the surface itself.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] In fact, it can be found given the full knowledge of the first fundamental form and expressed via the first fundamental form and its partial derivatives of first and second order.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Equivalently, the determinant of the second fundamental form of a surface in **R**3 can be so expressed.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] In particular, the Gaussian curvature is invariant under isometric deformations of the surface.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] In contemporary differential geometry, a "surface", viewed abstractly, is a two-dimensional differentiable manifold.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] To connect this point of view with the classical theory of surfaces, such an abstract surface is embedded into **R**3 and endowed with the Riemannian metric given by the first fundamental form.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Suppose that the image of the embedding is a surface S in **R**3.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] A *local isometry* is a diffeomorphism *f* : *U* → *V* between open regions of **R**3 whose restriction to *S* ∩ *U* is an isometry onto its image.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The Gaussian curvature of an embedded smooth surface in **R**3 is invariant under the local isometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] For example, the Gaussian curvature of a cylindrical tube is zero, the same as for the "unrolled" tube (which is flat).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] On the other hand, since a sphere of radius R has constant positive curvature *R*−2 and a flat plane has constant curvature 0, these two surfaces are not isometric, not even locally.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Thus any planar representation of even a small part of a sphere must distort the distances.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Therefore, no cartographic projection is perfect.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] The Gauss–Bonnet theorem relates the total curvature of a surface to its Euler characteristic and provides an important link between local geometric properties and global topological properties.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] There are other surfaces which have constant positive Gaussian curvature.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Manfredo do Carmo considers surfaces of revolution $(\phi (v)\cos(u),\phi (v)\sin(u),\psi (v))$ where $\phi (v)=C\cos v$ , and ${\textstyle \psi (v)=\int _{0}^{v}{\sqrt {1-C^{2}\sin ^{2}v'}}\ dv'}$ (an incomplete Elliptic integral of the second kind).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] These surfaces all have constant Gaussian curvature of 1, but, for $C\neq 1$ either have a boundary or a singular point. do Carmo also gives three different examples of surface with constant negative Gaussian curvature, one of which is pseudosphere.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] There are many other possible bounded surfaces with constant Gaussian curvature.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Whilst the sphere is rigid and can not be bent using an isometry, if a small region removed, or even a cut along a small segment, then the resulting surface can be bent.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/gaussian-curvature] Such bending preserves Gaussian curvature so any such bending of a sphere with a region removed will also have constant Gaussian curvature.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In mathematics, **hyperbolic geometry** (also called **Lobachevskian geometry** or **Bolyai–Lobachevskian geometry**) is a non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The **hyperbolic plane** is a plane where every point is a saddle point.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Hyperbolic plane geometry is also the geometry of pseudospherical surfaces, surfaces with a constant negative Gaussian curvature.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Saddle surfaces have negative Gaussian curvature in at least some regions, where they locally resemble the hyperbolic plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The hyperboloid model of hyperbolic geometry provides a representation of events one temporal unit into the future in Minkowski space, the basis of special relativity.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Each of these events corresponds to a rapidity in some direction.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In the former Soviet Union, it is commonly called Lobachevskian geometry, named after one of its discoverers, the Russian geometer Nikolai Lobachevsky.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Hyperbolic geometry is more closely related to Euclidean geometry than it seems: the only axiomatic difference is the parallel postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] When the parallel postulate is removed from Euclidean geometry the resulting geometry is absolute geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] There are two kinds of absolute geometry, Euclidean and hyperbolic.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] All theorems of absolute geometry, including the first 28 propositions of book one of Euclid's *Elements*, are valid in Euclidean and hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Propositions 27 and 28 of Book One of Euclid's *Elements* prove the existence of parallel/non-intersecting lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This difference also has many consequences: concepts that are equivalent in Euclidean geometry are not equivalent in hyperbolic geometry; new concepts need to be introduced.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Further, because of the angle of parallelism, hyperbolic geometry has an absolute scale, a relation between distance and angle measurements.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Single lines in hyperbolic geometry have exactly the same properties as single straight lines in Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For example, two points uniquely define a line, and line segments can be infinitely extended.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Two intersecting lines have the same properties as two intersecting lines in Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For example, two distinct lines can intersect in no more than one point, intersecting lines form equal opposite angles, and adjacent angles of intersecting lines are supplementary.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] When a third line is introduced, then there can be properties of intersecting lines that differ from intersecting lines in Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For example, given two intersecting lines there are infinitely many lines that do not intersect either of the given lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] These properties are all independent of the model used, even if the lines may look radically different.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This implies that there are through *P* an infinite number of coplanar lines that do not intersect *R*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Some geometers simply use the phrase "*parallel* lines" to mean "*limiting parallel* lines", with *ultraparallel* lines meaning just *non-intersecting*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] These limiting parallels make an angle *θ* with *PB*; this angle depends only on the Gaussian curvature of the plane and the distance *PB* and is called the angle of parallelism.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For ultraparallel lines, the ultraparallel theorem states that there is a unique line in the hyperbolic plane that is perpendicular to each pair of ultraparallel lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In hyperbolic geometry, the circumference of a circle of radius *r* is greater than $2\pi r$ .
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Let $R={\frac {1}{\sqrt {-K}}}$ , where K is the Gaussian curvature of the plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In hyperbolic geometry, K is negative, so the square root is of a positive number.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Therefore, in hyperbolic geometry the ratio of a circle's circumference to its radius is always strictly greater than $2\pi$ , though it can be made arbitrarily close by selecting a small enough circle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In hyperbolic geometry, there is no line whose points are all equidistant from another line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Instead, the points that are all the same distance from a given line lie on a curve called a hypercycle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Another special curve is the horocycle, whose normal radii (perpendicular lines) are all limiting parallel to each other (all converge asymptotically in one direction to the same ideal point, the centre of the horocycle).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Through every pair of points there are two horocycles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The centres of the horocycles are the ideal points of the perpendicular bisector of the line-segment between them.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Given any three distinct points, they all lie on either a line, hypercycle, horocycle, or circle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The **length** of a line-segment is the shortest length between two points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The arc-length of a hypercycle connecting two points is longer than that of the line segment and shorter than that of the arc horocycle, connecting the same two points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The lengths of the arcs of both horocycles connecting two points are equal, and are longer than the arclength of any hypercycle connecting the points and shorter than the arc of any circle connecting the two points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] If the Gaussian curvature of the plane is −1, then the geodesic curvature of a horocycle is 1 and that of a hypercycle is between 0 and 1.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Unlike Euclidean triangles, where the angles always add up to π radians (180°, a straight angle), in hyperbolic space the sum of the angles of a triangle is always strictly less than π radians (180°).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Generally, the defect of a convex hyperbolic polygon with n sides is its angle sum subtracted from $(n-2)\cdot 180^{\circ }$ .
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The area of a hyperbolic triangle is given by its defect in radians multiplied by *R*2, which is also true for all convex hyperbolic polygons.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Therefore, all hyperbolic triangles have an area less than or equal to *R*2π.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The area of a hyperbolic ideal triangle in which all three angles are 0° is equal to this maximum.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] As in Euclidean geometry, each hyperbolic triangle has an incircle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In hyperbolic space, if all three of its vertices lie on a horocycle or hypercycle, then the triangle has no circumscribed circle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] As in spherical and elliptical geometry, in hyperbolic geometry if two triangles are similar, they must be congruent.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Special polygons in hyperbolic geometry are the regular apeirogon and **pseudogon** uniform polygons with an infinite number of sides.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In Euclidean geometry, the only way to construct such a polygon is to make the side lengths tend to zero and the apeirogon is indistinguishable from a circle, or make the interior angles tend to 180° and the apeirogon approaches a straight line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] However, in hyperbolic geometry, a regular apeirogon or pseudogon has sides of any length (i.e., it remains a polygon with noticeable sides).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The side and angle bisectors will, depending on the side length and the angle between the sides, be limiting or diverging parallel.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] If the bisectors are limiting parallel then it is an apeirogon and can be inscribed and circumscribed by concentric horocycles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] If the bisectors are diverging parallel then it is a pseudogon and can be inscribed and circumscribed by hypercycles (since all its vertices are the same distance from a line, the axis, and the midpoints of its sides are also equidistant from that same axis).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Like the Euclidean plane it is also possible to tessellate the hyperbolic plane with regular polygons as faces.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] There are an infinite number of uniform tilings based on the Schwarz triangles (*p* *q* *r*) where 1/*p* + 1/*q* + 1/*r* < 1, where *p*, *q*, *r* are each orders of reflection symmetry at three points of the fundamental domain triangle, the symmetry group is a hyperbolic triangle group.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] There are also infinitely many uniform tilings that cannot be generated from Schwarz triangles, some for example requiring quadrilaterals as fundamental domains.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Though hyperbolic geometry applies for any surface with a constant negative Gaussian curvature, it is usual to assume a scale in which the curvature *K* is −1.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This results in some formulas becoming simpler.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] There are however different coordinate systems for hyperbolic plane geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] All are based around choosing a point (the origin) on a chosen directed line (the *x*-axis) and after that many choices exist.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The Lobachevsky coordinates *x* and *y* are found by dropping a perpendicular onto the *x*-axis.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] *x* will be the label of the foot of the perpendicular.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] *y* will be the distance along the perpendicular of the given point from its foot (positive on one side and negative on the other).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Another coordinate system measures the distance from the point to the horocycle through the origin centered around $(0,+\infty )$ and the length along this horocycle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Other coordinate systems use the Klein model or the Poincaré disk model described below, and take the Euclidean coordinates as hyperbolic.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] A Cartesian-like coordinate system (*x, y*) on the oriented hyperbolic plane is constructed as follows.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Choose a line in the hyperbolic plane together with an orientation and an origin *o* on this line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This formula can be derived from the formulas about hyperbolic triangles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Generally, these equations will only hold in a bounded domain (of *x* values).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] At the edge of that domain, the value of *y* blows up to ±infinity.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Since the publication of Euclid's *Elements* around 300 BC, many geometers tried to prove the parallel postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Some tried to prove it by assuming its negation and trying to derive a contradiction.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Foremost among these were Proclus, Ibn al-Haytham (Alhacen), Omar Khayyám, Nasīr al-Dīn al-Tūsī, Witelo, Gersonides, Alfonso, and later Giovanni Gerolamo Saccheri, John Wallis, Johann Heinrich Lambert, and Legendre.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Their attempts were doomed to failure (as we now know, the parallel postulate is not provable from the other postulates), but their efforts led to the discovery of hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The theorems of Alhacen, Khayyam and al-Tūsī on quadrilaterals, including the Ibn al-Haytham–Lambert quadrilateral and Khayyam–Saccheri quadrilateral, were the first theorems on hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Their works on hyperbolic geometry had a considerable influence on its development among later European geometers, including Witelo, Gersonides, Alfonso, John Wallis and Saccheri.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In the 18th century, Johann Heinrich Lambert introduced the hyperbolic functions and computed the area of a hyperbolic triangle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In the 19th century, hyperbolic geometry was explored extensively by Nikolai Lobachevsky, János Bolyai, Carl Friedrich Gauss and Franz Taurinus.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Unlike their predecessors, who just wanted to eliminate the parallel postulate from the axioms of Euclidean geometry, these authors realized they had discovered a new geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Gauss wrote in an 1824 letter to Franz Taurinus that he had constructed it, but Gauss did not publish his work.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Gauss called it "non-Euclidean geometry" causing several modern authors to continue to consider "non-Euclidean geometry" and "hyperbolic geometry" to be synonyms.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Taurinus published results on hyperbolic trigonometry in 1826, argued that hyperbolic geometry is self-consistent, but still believed in the special role of Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The complete system of hyperbolic geometry was published by Lobachevsky in 1829/1830, while Bolyai discovered it independently and published in 1832.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In 1868, Eugenio Beltrami provided models of hyperbolic geometry, and used this to prove that hyperbolic geometry was consistent if and only if Euclidean geometry was.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The term "hyperbolic geometry" was introduced by Felix Klein in 1871.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Klein followed an initiative of Arthur Cayley to use the transformations of projective geometry to produce isometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The idea used a conic section or quadric to define a region, and used cross ratio to define a metric.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The projective transformations that leave the conic section or quadric stable are the isometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The discovery of hyperbolic geometry had important philosophical consequences.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Before its discovery many philosophers (such as Hobbes and Spinoza) viewed philosophical rigor in terms of the "geometrical method", referring to the method of reasoning used in Euclid's *Elements*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Kant in *Critique of Pure Reason* concluded that space (in Euclidean geometry) and time are not discovered by humans as objective features of the world, but are part of an unavoidable systematic framework for organizing our experiences.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] It is said that Gauss did not publish anything about hyperbolic geometry out of fear of the "uproar of the Boeotians" (stereotyped as dullards by the ancient Athenians), which would ruin his status as *princeps mathematicorum* (Latin, "the Prince of Mathematicians").
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The "uproar of the Boeotians" came and went, and gave an impetus to great improvements in mathematical rigour, analytical philosophy and logic.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Hyperbolic geometry was finally proved consistent and is therefore another valid geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Because Euclidean, hyperbolic and elliptic geometry are all consistent, the question arises: which is the real geometry of space, and if it is hyperbolic or elliptic, what is its curvature?
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Lobachevsky had already tried to measure the curvature of the universe by measuring the parallax of Sirius and treating Sirius as the ideal point of an angle of parallelism.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] He realized that his measurements were not precise enough to give a definite answer, but he did reach the conclusion that if the geometry of the universe is hyperbolic, then the absolute length is at least one million times the diameter of Earth's orbit (2000000 AU, 10 parsec).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Some argue that his measurements were methodologically flawed.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Henri Poincaré, with his sphere-world thought experiment, came to the conclusion that everyday experience does not necessarily rule out other geometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The geometrization conjecture gives a complete list of eight possibilities for the fundamental geometry of our space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The problem in determining which one applies is that, to reach a definitive answer, we need to be able to look at extremely large shapes – much larger than anything on Earth or perhaps even in our galaxy.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Special relativity places space and time on equal footing, so that one considers the geometry of a unified spacetime instead of considering space and time separately.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Minkowski geometry replaces Galilean geometry (which is the 3-dimensional Euclidean space with time of Galilean relativity).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In relativity, rather than Euclidean, elliptic and hyperbolic geometry, the appropriate geometries to consider are Minkowski space, de Sitter space and anti-de Sitter space, corresponding to zero, positive and negative curvature respectively.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Hyperbolic geometry enters special relativity through rapidity, which stands in for velocity, and is expressed by a hyperbolic angle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The study of this velocity geometry has been called kinematic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The space of relativistic velocities has a three-dimensional hyperbolic geometry, where the distance function is determined from the relative velocities of "nearby" points (velocities).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] There exist various pseudospheres in Euclidean space that have a finite area of constant negative Gaussian curvature.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] By Hilbert's theorem, one cannot isometrically immerse a complete hyperbolic plane (a complete regular surface of constant negative Gaussian curvature) in a 3-D Euclidean space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Other useful models of hyperbolic geometry exist in Euclidean space, in which the metric is not preserved.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] A particularly well-known paper model based on the pseudosphere is due to William Thurston.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The art of crochet has been used to demonstrate hyperbolic planes, the first such demonstration having been made by Daina Taimiņa.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In 2000, Keith Henderson demonstrated a quick-to-make paper model dubbed the "hyperbolic soccerball" (more precisely, a truncated order-7 triangular tiling).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Instructions on how to make a hyperbolic quilt, designed by Helaman Ferguson, have been made available by Jeff Weeks.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Various pseudospheres – surfaces with constant negative Gaussian curvature – can be embedded in 3-D space under the standard Euclidean metric, and so can be made into tangible models.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Of these, the tractoid (or pseudosphere) is the best known; using the tractoid as a model of the hyperbolic plane is analogous to using a cone or cylinder as a model of the Euclidean plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] However, the entire hyperbolic plane cannot be embedded into Euclidean space in this way, and various other models are more convenient for abstractly exploring hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] There are four models commonly used for hyperbolic geometry: the Klein model, the Poincaré disk model, the Poincaré half-plane model, and the Lorentz or hyperboloid model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] These models define a hyperbolic plane which satisfies the axioms of a hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Despite their names, the first three mentioned above were introduced as models of hyperbolic space by Beltrami, not by Poincaré or Klein.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] All these models are extendable to more dimensions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The Beltrami–Klein model, also known as the projective disk model, Klein disk model and Klein model, is named after Eugenio Beltrami and Felix Klein.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For the two dimensions this model uses the interior of the unit circle for the complete hyperbolic plane, and the chords of this circle are the hyperbolic lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For higher dimensions this model uses the interior of the unit ball, and the chords of this *n*-ball are the hyperbolic lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The Poincaré disk model, also known as the conformal disk model, also employs the interior of the unit circle, but lines are represented by arcs of circles that are orthogonal to the boundary circle, plus diameters of the boundary circle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The Poincaré half-plane model takes one-half of the Euclidean plane, bounded by a line *B* of the plane, to be a model of the hyperbolic plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The line *B* is not included in the model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The Euclidean plane may be taken to be a plane with the Cartesian coordinate system and the x-axis is taken as line *B* and the half plane is the upper half (*y* > 0 ) of this plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The hyperboloid model or Lorentz model employs a 2-dimensional hyperboloid of revolution (of two sheets, but using one) embedded in 3-dimensional Minkowski space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This model is generally credited to Poincaré, but Reynolds says that Wilhelm Killing used this model in 1885.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The hemisphere model is not often used as model by itself, but it functions as a useful tool for visualizing transformations between the other models.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The hyperbolic lines are half-circles orthogonal to the boundary of the hemisphere.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] All models essentially describe the same structure.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The difference between them is that they represent different coordinate charts laid down on the same metric space, namely the hyperbolic plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The characteristic feature of the hyperbolic plane itself is that it has a constant negative Gaussian curvature, which is indifferent to the coordinate chart used.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The geodesics are similarly invariant: that is, geodesics map to geodesics under coordinate transformation.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Hyperbolic geometry is generally introduced in terms of the geodesics and their intersections on the hyperbolic plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Once we choose a coordinate chart (one of the "models"), we can always embed it in a Euclidean space of same dimension, but the embedding is clearly not isometric (since the curvature of Euclidean space is 0).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The hyperbolic space can be represented by infinitely many different charts; but the embeddings in Euclidean space due to these four specific charts show some interesting characteristics.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Since the four models describe the same metric space, each can be transformed into the other.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In 1966 David Gans proposed a flattened hyperboloid model in the journal *American Mathematical Monthly*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] It is an orthographic projection of the hyperboloid model onto the xy-plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This model is not as widely used as other models but nevertheless is quite useful in the understanding of hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The conformal square model of the hyperbolic plane arises from using Schwarz–Christoffel mapping to convert the Poincaré disk into a square.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This model has finite extent, like the Poincaré disk.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] However, all of the points are inside a square.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This model is conformal, which makes it suitable for artistic applications.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The band model employs a portion of the Euclidean plane between two parallel lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Distance is preserved along one line through the middle of the band.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Assuming the band is given by $\{z\in \mathbb {C} :|\operatorname {Im} z|<\pi /2\}$ , the metric is given by $|dz|\sec(\operatorname {Im} z)$ .
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Every isometry (transformation or motion) of the hyperbolic plane to itself can be realized as the composition of at most three reflections.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In *n*-dimensional hyperbolic space, up to *n*+1 reflections might be required.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Escher's famous prints *Circle Limit III* and *Circle Limit IV* illustrate the conformal disc model (Poincaré disk model) quite well.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The white lines in *III* are not quite geodesics (they are hypercycles), but are close to them.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] It is also possible to see the negative curvature of the hyperbolic plane, through its effect on the sum of angles in triangles and squares.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For example, in *Circle Limit III* every vertex belongs to three triangles and three squares.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In the Euclidean plane, their angles would sum to 450°; i.e., a circle and a quarter.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] From this, we see that the sum of angles of a triangle in the hyperbolic plane must be smaller than 180°.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Another visible property is exponential growth.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In *Circle Limit III*, for example, one can see that the number of fishes within a distance of *n* from the center rises exponentially.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The fishes have an equal hyperbolic area, so the area of a ball of radius *n* must rise exponentially in *n*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The art of crochet has been used to demonstrate hyperbolic planes (pictured above) with the first being made by Daina Taimiņa, whose book *Crocheting Adventures with Hyperbolic Planes* won the 2009 *Bookseller*/Diagram Prize for Oddest Title of the Year.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Hyperbolic geometry is not limited to 2 dimensions; a hyperbolic geometry exists for every higher number of dimensions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The orthogonal group O(1, *n*) acts by norm-preserving transformations on Minkowski space **R**1,*n*, and it acts transitively on the two-sheet hyperboloid of norm 1 vectors.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] Timelike lines (i.e., those with positive-norm tangents) through the origin pass through antipodal points in the hyperboloid, so the space of such lines yields a model of hyperbolic *n*-space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The stabilizer of any particular line is isomorphic to the product of the orthogonal groups O(*n*) and O(1), where O(*n*) acts on the tangent space of a point in the hyperboloid, and O(1) reflects the line through the origin.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In small dimensions, there are exceptional isomorphisms of Lie groups that yield additional ways to consider symmetries of hyperbolic spaces.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For example, in dimension 2, the isomorphisms SO+(1, 2) ≅ PSL(2, **R**) ≅ PSU(1, 1) allow one to interpret the upper half plane model as the quotient SL(2, **R**)/SO(2) and the Poincaré disc model as the quotient SU(1, 1)/U(1).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In both cases, the symmetry groups act by fractional linear transformations, since both groups are the orientation-preserving stabilizers in PGL(2, **C**) of the respective subspaces of the Riemann sphere.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] The Cayley transformation not only takes one model of the hyperbolic plane to the other, but realizes the isomorphism of symmetry groups as conjugation in a larger group.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] In dimension 3, the fractional linear action of PGL(2, **C**) on the Riemann sphere is identified with the action on the conformal boundary of hyperbolic 3-space induced by the isomorphism O+(1, 3) ≅ PGL(2, **C**).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] This allows one to study isometries of hyperbolic 3-space by considering spectral properties of representative complex matrices.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/hyperbolic-geometry] For example, parabolic transformations are conjugate to rigid translations in the upper half-space model, and they are exactly those transformations that can be represented by unipotent upper triangular matrices.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In mathematics, **non-Euclidean geometry** consists of two geometries based on axioms closely related to those that specify Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] As Euclidean geometry lies at the intersection of metric geometry and affine geometry, non-Euclidean geometry arises by either replacing the parallel postulate with an alternative, or consideration of quadratic forms other than the definite quadratic forms associated with metric geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In the former case, one obtains hyperbolic geometry and elliptic geometry, the traditional non-Euclidean geometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] When isotropic quadratic forms are admitted, then there are affine planes associated with the planar algebras, which give rise to kinematic geometries that have also been called non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The essential difference between the metric geometries is the nature of parallel lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Euclid's fifth postulate, the parallel postulate, is equivalent to Playfair's postulate, which states that, within a two-dimensional plane, for any given line l and a point *p*, which is not on l, there is exactly one line through *p* that does not intersect l.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In hyperbolic geometry, by contrast, there are infinitely many lines through *p* not intersecting l, while in elliptic geometry, any line through *p* intersects l.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Euclidean geometry, named after the Greek mathematician Euclid, includes some of the oldest known mathematics, and geometries that deviated from this were not widely accepted as legitimate until the 19th century.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The debate that eventually led to the discovery of the non-Euclidean geometries began almost as soon as Euclid wrote *Elements*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In the *Elements*, Euclid begins with a limited number of assumptions (23 definitions, five common notions, and five postulates) and seeks to prove all the other results (propositions) in the work.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Other mathematicians have devised simpler forms of this property.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] To produce [extend] a finite straight line continuously in a straight line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] To describe a circle with any centre and distance [radius].
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] That all right angles are equal to one another.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] For at least a thousand years, geometers were troubled by the disparate complexity of the fifth postulate, and believed it could be proved as a theorem from the other four.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Many attempted to find a proof by contradiction, including Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen, 11th century), Omar Khayyám (12th century), Nasīr al-Dīn al-Tūsī (13th century), and Giovanni Girolamo Saccheri (18th century).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The theorems of Ibn al-Haytham, Khayyam and al-Tusi on quadrilaterals, including the Lambert quadrilateral and Saccheri quadrilateral, were "the first few theorems of the hyperbolic and the elliptic geometries".
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] These theorems along with their alternative postulates, such as Playfair's axiom, played an important role in the later development of non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] These early attempts at challenging the fifth postulate had a considerable influence on its development among later European geometers, including Witelo, Levi ben Gerson, Alfonso, John Wallis and Saccheri.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] All of these early attempts made at trying to formulate non-Euclidean geometry, however, provided flawed proofs of the parallel postulate, depending on assumptions that are now recognized as essentially equivalent to the parallel postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] These early attempts did, however, provide some early properties of the hyperbolic and elliptic geometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Another example is al-Tusi's son, Sadr al-Din (sometimes known as "Pseudo-Tusi"), who wrote a book on the subject in 1298, based on al-Tusi's later thoughts, which presented another hypothesis equivalent to the parallel postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] "He essentially revised both the Euclidean system of axioms and postulates and the proofs of many propositions from the *Elements*." His work was published in Rome in 1594 and was studied by European geometers, including Saccheri who criticised this work as well as that of Wallis.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Giordano Vitale, in his book *Euclide restituo* (1680, 1686), used the Saccheri quadrilateral to prove that if three points are equidistant on the base AB and the summit CD, then AB and CD are everywhere equidistant.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] He finally reached a point where he believed that his results demonstrated the impossibility of hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] His claim seems to have been based on Euclidean presuppositions, because no *logical* contradiction was present.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In this attempt to prove Euclidean geometry he instead unintentionally discovered a new viable geometry, but did not realize it.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In 1766 Johann Lambert wrote, but did not publish, *Theorie der Parallellinien* in which he attempted, as Saccheri did, to prove the fifth postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] He worked with a figure now known as a *Lambert quadrilateral*, a quadrilateral with three right angles (can be considered half of a Saccheri quadrilateral).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] He quickly eliminated the possibility that the fourth angle is obtuse, as had Saccheri and Khayyam, and then proceeded to prove many theorems under the assumption of an acute angle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Unlike Saccheri, he never felt that he had reached a contradiction with this assumption.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] He had proved the non-Euclidean result that the sum of the angles in a triangle increases as the area of the triangle decreases, and this led him to speculate on the possibility of a model of the acute case on a sphere of imaginary radius.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] At this time it was widely believed that the universe worked according to the principles of Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The beginning of the 19th century would finally witness decisive steps in the creation of non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Circa 1813, Carl Friedrich Gauss and independently around 1818, the German professor of law Ferdinand Karl Schweikart had the germinal ideas of non-Euclidean geometry worked out.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Schweikart published his results in his book of 1807 .
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] According to George Bruce Halsted , "Schweikart may be considered the first to publish a genuine conscious treatise on Non-Euclidean Geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Then, in 1829–1830 the Russian mathematician Nikolai Ivanovich Lobachevsky and in 1832 the Hungarian mathematician János Bolyai separately and independently published treatises on hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Consequently, hyperbolic geometry is called Lobachevskian or Bolyai-Lobachevskian geometry, as both mathematicians, independent of each other, are the basic authors of non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Gauss mentioned to Bolyai's father, when shown the younger Bolyai's work, that he had developed such a geometry several years before, though he did not publish.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] While Lobachevsky created a non-Euclidean geometry by negating the parallel postulate, Bolyai worked out a geometry where both the Euclidean and the hyperbolic geometry are possible depending on a parameter *k*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Bolyai ends his work by mentioning that it is not possible to decide through mathematical reasoning alone if the geometry of the physical universe is Euclidean or non-Euclidean; this is a task for the physical sciences.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Bernhard Riemann, in a famous lecture in 1854, founded the field of Riemannian geometry, discussing in particular the ideas now called manifolds, Riemannian metric, and curvature.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] He constructed an infinite family of non-Euclidean geometries by giving a formula for a family of Riemannian metrics on the unit ball in Euclidean space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The simplest of these is called elliptic geometry and it is considered a non-Euclidean geometry due to its lack of parallel lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] By formulating the geometry in terms of a curvature tensor, Riemann allowed non-Euclidean geometry to apply to higher dimensions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Beltrami (1868) was the first to apply Riemann's geometry to spaces of negative curvature.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] It was Gauss who coined the term "non-Euclidean geometry".
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] He was referring to his own work, which today we call *hyperbolic geometry* or *Lobachevskian geometry*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Several modern authors still use the generic term *non-Euclidean geometry* to mean *hyperbolic geometry*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Arthur Cayley noted that distance between points inside a conic could be defined in terms of logarithm and the projective cross-ratio function.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The method has become called the Cayley–Klein metric because Felix Klein exploited it to describe the non-Euclidean geometries in articles in 1871 and 1873 and later in book form.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The Cayley–Klein metrics provided working models of hyperbolic and elliptic metric geometries, as well as Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Klein is responsible for the terms "hyperbolic" and "elliptic" (in his system he called Euclidean geometry *parabolic*, a term that generally fell out of use).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] His influence has led to the current usage of the term "non-Euclidean geometry" to mean either "hyperbolic" or "elliptic" geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] There are some mathematicians who would extend the list of geometries that should be called "non-Euclidean" in various ways.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] There are many kinds of geometry that are quite different from Euclidean geometry but are also not necessarily included in the conventional meaning of "non-Euclidean geometry", such as more general instances of Riemannian geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Euclidean geometry can be axiomatically described in several ways.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] However, Euclid's original system of five postulates (axioms) is not one of these, as his proofs relied on several unstated assumptions that should also have been taken as axioms.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Hilbert's system consisting of 20 axioms most closely follows the approach of Euclid and provides the justification for all of Euclid's proofs.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Other systems, using different sets of undefined terms obtain the same geometry by different paths.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] All approaches, however, have an axiom that is logically equivalent to Euclid's fifth postulate, the parallel postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] As the first 28 propositions of Euclid (in *The Elements*) do not require the use of the parallel postulate or anything equivalent to it, they are all true statements in absolute geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] To obtain a non-Euclidean geometry, the parallel postulate (or its equivalent) *must* be replaced by its negation.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Negating the Playfair's axiom form, since it is a compound statement (... there exists one and only one ...), can be done in two ways: either there will exist more than one line through the point parallel to the given line or there will exist no lines through the point parallel to the given line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Euclidean geometry is modelled by our notion of a "flat plane." The simplest model for elliptic geometry is a sphere, where lines are "great circles" (such as the equator or the meridians on a globe), and points opposite each other are identified (considered to be the same).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The pseudosphere has the appropriate curvature to model hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The simplest model for elliptic geometry is a sphere, where lines are "great circles" (such as the equator or the meridians on a globe), and points opposite each other (called antipodal points) are identified (considered the same).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] This is also one of the standard models of the real projective plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The difference is that as a model of elliptic geometry a metric is introduced permitting the measurement of lengths and angles, while as a model of the projective plane there is no such metric.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In the elliptic model, for any given line l and a point *A*, which is not on l, all lines through *A* will intersect l.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Even after the work of Lobachevsky, Gauss, and Bolyai, the question remained: "Does such a model exist for hyperbolic geometry?".
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In the hyperbolic model, within a two-dimensional plane, for any given line l and a point *A*, which is not on l, there are infinitely many lines through *A* that do not intersect l.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In these models, the concepts of non-Euclidean geometries are represented by Euclidean objects in a Euclidean setting.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] This introduces a perceptual distortion wherein the straight lines of the non-Euclidean geometry are represented by Euclidean curves that visually bend.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] This "bending" is not a property of the non-Euclidean lines, only an artifice of the way they are represented.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] In three dimensions, there are eight models of geometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Euclidean and non-Euclidean geometries naturally have many similar properties, namely those that do not depend upon the nature of parallelism.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] This commonality is the subject of absolute geometry (also called *neutral geometry*).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] However, the properties that distinguish one geometry from others have historically received the most attention.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Before the models of a non-Euclidean plane were presented by Beltrami, Klein, and Poincaré, Euclidean geometry stood unchallenged as the mathematical model of space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Furthermore, since the substance of the subject in synthetic geometry was a chief exhibit of rationality, the Euclidean point of view represented absolute authority.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The discovery of the non-Euclidean geometries had a ripple effect which went far beyond the boundaries of mathematics and science.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The philosopher Immanuel Kant's treatment of human knowledge had a special role for geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] It was his prime example of synthetic a priori knowledge; not derived from the senses nor deduced through logic—our knowledge of space was a truth that we were born with.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Unfortunately for Kant, his concept of this unalterably true geometry was Euclidean.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Theology was also affected by the change from absolute truth to relative truth in the way that mathematics is related to the world around it, that was a result of this paradigm shift.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Non-Euclidean geometry is an example of a scientific revolution in the history of science, in which mathematicians and scientists changed the way they viewed their subjects.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Some geometers called Lobachevsky the "Copernicus of Geometry" due to the revolutionary character of his work.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The existence of non-Euclidean geometries impacted the intellectual life of Victorian England in many ways and in particular was one of the leading factors that caused a re-examination of the teaching of geometry based on Euclid's Elements.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] This curriculum issue was hotly debated at the time and was even the subject of a book, *Euclid and his Modern Rivals*, written by Charles Lutwidge Dodgson (1832–1898) better known as Lewis Carroll, the author of *Alice in Wonderland*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The points are sometimes identified with generalized complex numbers *z* = *x* + *y* ε where ε2 ∈ { –1, 0, 1 }.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The Euclidean plane corresponds to the case ε2 = −1, an imaginary unit.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] For instance, {*z* | *z z** = 1} is the unit circle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] For planar algebra, non-Euclidean geometry arises in the other cases.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Then z is a split-complex number and conventionally **j** replaces epsilon.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] and {*z* | *z z** = 1} is the unit hyperbola.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] This approach to non-Euclidean geometry explains the non-Euclidean angles: the parameters of slope in the dual number plane and hyperbolic angle in the split-complex plane correspond to angle in Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Indeed, they each arise in polar decomposition of a complex number z.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Hyperbolic geometry found an application in kinematics with the physical cosmology introduced by Hermann Minkowski in 1908.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Minkowski introduced terms like worldline and proper time into mathematical physics.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] He realized that the submanifold, of events one moment of proper time into the future, could be considered a hyperbolic space of three dimensions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Already in the 1890s Alexander Macfarlane was charting this submanifold through his *Algebra of Physics* and hyperbolic quaternions, though Macfarlane did not use cosmological language as Minkowski did in 1908.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The relevant structure is now called the hyperboloid model of hyperbolic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] The non-Euclidean planar algebras support kinematic geometries in the plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] For instance, the split-complex number *z* = e*a*j can represent a spacetime event one moment into the future of a frame of reference of rapidity *a*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Furthermore, multiplication by *z* amounts to a Lorentz boost mapping the frame with rapidity zero to that with rapidity *a*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Another view of special relativity as a non-Euclidean geometry was advanced by E.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Wilson and Gilbert Lewis in *Proceedings of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences* in 1912.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] They revamped the analytic geometry implicit in the split-complex number algebra into synthetic geometry of premises and deductions.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/non-euclidean-geometry] Non-Euclidean geometry often makes appearances in works of science fiction and fantasy.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] In geometry, the **parallel postulate** is the fifth postulate in Euclid's *Elements* and a distinctive axiom in Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] This latter assertion is proved in Euclid's *Elements* by using the fact that two different lines have at most one intersection point.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Conversely this latter assertion implies that two different lines cannot have two intersection points (draw a line passing between the two intersection points and apply the assertion to both sides of this line).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] This original formulation of the postulate does not specifically talk about parallel lines; however, its converse and the second formulation imply the existence of parallel lines, since, if the interior angles sum to two right angles, then the two lines do not intersect.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Euclid gave the definition of parallel lines in Book I, Definition 23 just before the five postulates.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The postulate was long considered to be obvious or inevitable, but proofs were elusive.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Eventually, it was discovered that inverting the postulate gave valid, albeit different geometries.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] A geometry where the parallel postulate or its converse does not hold is known as a non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] A geometry that is independent of Euclid's fifth postulate and assumes that two different lines have at most one intersection point (i.e., only assumes the modern equivalent of the first four postulates) is known as an absolute geometry (or sometimes "neutral geometry").
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] This axiom by itself is not logically equivalent to the Euclidean parallel postulate since there are geometries in which one is true and the other is not.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] However, in the presence of the remaining axioms which give Euclidean geometry, one can be used to prove the other, so they are equivalent in the context of absolute geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The sum of the angles in every triangle is 180° (triangle postulate).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] There exists a triangle whose angles add up to 180°.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The sum of the angles is the same for every triangle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] There exists a pair of similar, but not congruent, triangles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] If three angles of a quadrilateral are right angles, then the fourth angle is also a right angle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] There exists a quadrilateral in which all angles are right angles, that is, a rectangle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] There exists a pair of straight lines that are at constant distance from each other.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Two lines that are parallel to the same line are also parallel to each other.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] In a right-angled triangle, the square of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides (Pythagoras' theorem).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The law of cosines, a generalization of Pythagoras' theorem.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] There is no upper limit to the area of a triangle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The summit angles of the Saccheri quadrilateral are 90°.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] If a line intersects one of two parallel lines, both of which are coplanar with the original line, then it also intersects the other.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] In the list above, it is always taken to refer to non-intersecting lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] However, if the definition is taken so that parallel lines are lines that do not intersect, or that have some line intersecting them in the same angles, Playfair's axiom is contextually equivalent to Euclid's fifth postulate and is thus logically independent of the first four postulates.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Note that the latter two definitions are not equivalent, because in hyperbolic geometry the second definition holds only for ultraparallel lines.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] From the beginning, the postulate came under attack as being provable, and therefore not a postulate, and for more than two thousand years, many attempts were made to prove (derive) the parallel postulate using Euclid's first four postulates.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The main reason that such a proof was so highly sought after was that, unlike the first four postulates, the parallel postulate is not self-evident.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] If the order in which the postulates were listed in the Elements is significant, it indicates that Euclid included this postulate only when he realised he could not prove it or proceed without it.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Many attempts were made to prove the fifth postulate from the other four, many of them being accepted as proofs for long periods until the mistake was found.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Invariably the mistake was assuming some 'obvious' property which turned out to be equivalent to the fifth postulate (Playfair's axiom).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Although known from the time of Proclus, this became known as Playfair's Axiom after John Playfair wrote a famous commentary on Euclid in 1795 in which he proposed replacing Euclid's fifth postulate by his own axiom.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Today, over two thousand two hundred years later, Euclid's fifth postulate remains a postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Proclus (410–485) wrote a commentary on *The Elements* where he comments on attempted proofs to deduce the fifth postulate from the other four; in particular, he notes that Ptolemy had produced a false 'proof'.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Proclus then goes on to give a false proof of his own.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] However, he did give a postulate which is equivalent to the fifth postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) (965–1039), an Arab mathematician, made an attempt at proving the parallel postulate using a proof by contradiction, in the course of which he introduced the concept of motion and transformation into geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] He formulated the Lambert quadrilateral, which Boris Abramovich Rozenfeld names the "Ibn al-Haytham–Lambert quadrilateral", and his attempted proof contains elements similar to those found in Lambert quadrilaterals and Playfair's axiom.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The Saccheri quadrilateral was also first considered by Omar Khayyám in the late 11th century in Book I of *Explanations of the Difficulties in the Postulates of Euclid*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Unlike many commentators on Euclid before and after him (including Giovanni Girolamo Saccheri), Khayyám was not trying to prove the parallel postulate as such but to derive it from his equivalent postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] He recognized that three possibilities arose from omitting Euclid's fifth postulate; if two perpendiculars to one line cross another line, judicious choice of the last can make the internal angles where it meets the two perpendiculars equal (it is then parallel to the first line).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] If those equal internal angles are right angles, we get Euclid's fifth postulate, otherwise, they must be either acute or obtuse.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] He showed that the acute and obtuse cases led to contradictions using his postulate, but his postulate is now known to be equivalent to the fifth postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Nasir al-Din al-Tusi (1201–1274), in his *Al-risala al-shafiya'an al-shakk fi'l-khutut al-mutawaziya* (*Discussion Which Removes Doubt about Parallel Lines*) (1250), wrote detailed critiques of the parallel postulate and on Khayyám's attempted proof a century earlier.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Nasir al-Din attempted to derive a proof by contradiction of the parallel postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] He also considered the cases of what are now known as elliptical and hyperbolic geometry, though he ruled out both of them.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Nasir al-Din's son, Sadr al-Din, wrote a book on the subject in 1298, based on his father's later thoughts, which presented one of the earliest arguments for a non-Euclidean hypothesis equivalent to the parallel postulate.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] "He essentially revised both the Euclidean system of axioms and postulates and the proofs of many propositions from the *Elements*." His work was published in Rome in 1594 and was studied by European geometers.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] This work marked the starting point for Saccheri's work on the subject which opened with a criticism of Sadr al-Din's work and the work of Wallis.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Giordano Vitale (1633–1711), in his book *Euclide restituto* (1680, 1686), used the Khayyam-Saccheri quadrilateral to prove that if three points are equidistant on the base AB and the summit CD, then AB and CD are everywhere equidistant.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] He worked with a figure that today we call a *Lambert quadrilateral*, a quadrilateral with three right angles (can be considered half of a Saccheri quadrilateral).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] He quickly eliminated the possibility that the fourth angle is obtuse, as had Saccheri and Khayyám, and then proceeded to prove many theorems under the assumption of an acute angle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Where Khayyám and Saccheri had attempted to prove Euclid's fifth by disproving the only possible alternatives, the nineteenth century finally saw mathematicians exploring those alternatives and discovering the logically consistent geometries that result.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] In 1829, Nikolai Ivanovich Lobachevsky published an account of acute geometry in an obscure Russian journal (later re-published in 1840 in German).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] In 1831, János Bolyai included, in a book by his father, an appendix describing acute geometry, which, doubtlessly, he had developed independently of Lobachevsky.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Carl Friedrich Gauss had also studied the problem, but he did not publish any of his results.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The resulting geometries were later developed by Lobachevsky, Riemann and Poincaré into hyperbolic geometry (the acute case) and elliptic geometry (the obtuse case).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The independence of the parallel postulate from Euclid's other axioms was finally demonstrated by Eugenio Beltrami in 1868.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Euclid did not postulate the converse of his fifth postulate, which is one way to distinguish Euclidean geometry from elliptic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] These results do not depend upon the fifth postulate, but they do require the second postulate which is violated in elliptic geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Attempts to logically prove the parallel postulate, rather than Euclid's Common Notion 4 (that figures coinciding with one another are equal to one another) were criticized by Arthur Schopenhauer in *The World as Will and Idea*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] However, the argument used by Schopenhauer was that the postulate is evident by perception, not that it was not a logical consequence of the other axioms.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The parallel postulate is equivalent to the conjunction of the Lotschnittaxiom and of Aristotle's axiom.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The former states that the perpendiculars to the sides of a right angle intersect, while the latter states that there is no upper bound for the lengths of the distances from the leg of an angle to the other leg.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Given three parallel lines, there is a line that intersects all three of them.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] Given a line *a* and two distinct intersecting lines *m* and *n*, each different from *a*, there exists a line *g* which intersects *a* and *m*, but not *n*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/parallel-postulate] The splitting of the parallel postulate into the conjunction of these incidence-geometric axioms is possible only in the presence of absolute geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The group of orientation preserving isometries of the disk model is given by the projective special unitary group PSU(1,1), the quotient of the special unitary group SU(1,1) by its center {*I*, −*I*}.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Along with the Klein model and the Poincaré half-space model, it was proposed by Eugenio Beltrami who used these models to show that hyperbolic geometry was equiconsistent with Euclidean geometry.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] It is named after Henri Poincaré, because his rediscovery of this representation fourteen years later became better known than the original work of Beltrami.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The **Poincaré ball model** is the similar model for *3* or *n*-dimensional hyperbolic geometry in which the points of the geometry are in the *n*-dimensional unit ball.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The disk model was first described by Bernhard Riemann in an 1854 lecture (published 1868), which inspired an 1868 paper by Eugenio Beltrami.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Henri Poincaré employed it in his 1882 treatment of hyperbolic, parabolic and elliptic functions, but it became widely known following Poincaré's presentation in his 1905 philosophical treatise, *Science and Hypothesis*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Poincaré's disk was an important piece of evidence for the hypothesis that the choice of spatial geometry is conventional rather than factual, especially in the influential philosophical discussions of Rudolf Carnap and of Hans Reichenbach.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Hyperbolic **straight lines** or geodesics consist of all arcs of Euclidean circles contained within the disk that are orthogonal to the boundary of the disk, plus all diameters of the disk.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Distances in this model are Cayley–Klein metrics.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Given two distinct points *p* and *q* inside the disk, the unique hyperbolic line connecting them intersects the boundary at two ideal points, *a* and *b*.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The vertical bars indicate Euclidean length of the line segment connecting the points between them in the model (not along the circle arc); ln is the natural logarithm.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] where $\lVert \cdot \rVert$ denotes the usual Euclidean norm.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Such a distance function is defined for any two vectors of norm less than one, and makes the set of such vectors into a metric space which is a model of hyperbolic space of constant curvature −1.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The model has the conformal property that the angle between two intersecting curves in hyperbolic space is the same as the angle in the model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] where the *x**i* are the Cartesian coordinates of the ambient Euclidean space.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] In two dimensions, with respect to these frames and the Levi-Civita connection, the connection forms are given by the unique skew-symmetric matrix of 1-forms $\omega$ that is torsion-free, i.e., that satisfies the matrix equation $0=d\theta +\omega \wedge \theta$ .
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] If P and Q are on a diameter of the boundary circle that diameter is the hyperbolic line.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] A basic construction of analytic geometry is to find a line through two given points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] which is the general form of a circle orthogonal to the unit circle, or else by diameters.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] We may compute the angle between the circular arc whose endpoints (*ideal points*) are given by unit vectors *u* and *v*, and the arc whose endpoints are *s* and *t*, by means of a formula.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Since the ideal points are the same in the Klein model and the Poincaré disk model, the formulas are identical for each model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] In the Euclidean plane the generalized circles (curves of constant curvature) are lines and circles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] On the sphere, they are great and small circles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] In the hyperbolic plane, there are 4 distinct types of generalized circles or *cycles*: circles, horocycles, hypercycles, and geodesics (or "hyperbolic lines").
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] In the Poincaré disk model, all of these are represented by straight lines or circles.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] A **circle** (the set of all points in a plane that are at a given distance from a given point, its center) is a circle completely inside the disk not touching or intersecting its boundary.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The hyperbolic center of the circle in the model does not in general correspond to the Euclidean center of the circle, but they are on the same radius of the Poincaré disk.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] A **hypercycle** (the set of all points in a plane that are on one side and at a given distance from a given line, its axis) is a Euclidean circle arc or chord of the boundary circle that intersects the boundary circle at a positive but non-right angle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Its axis is the hyperbolic line that shares the same two ideal points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] This is also known as an equidistant curve.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] A **horocycle** (a curve whose normal or perpendicular geodesics are limiting parallels, all converging asymptotically to the same ideal point), is a circle inside the disk that is tangent to the boundary circle of the disk.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The point where it touches the boundary circle is not part of the horocycle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] It is an ideal point and is the hyperbolic center of the horocycle.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] It is also the point to which all the perpendicular geodesics converge.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] In the Poincaré disk model, the Euclidean points representing opposite "ends" of a horocycle converge to its center on the boundary circle, but in the hyperbolic plane every point of a horocycle is infinitely far from its center, and opposite ends of the horocycle are not connected.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The Beltrami–Klein model (or Klein disk model) and the Poincaré disk are both models that project the whole hyperbolic plane in a disk.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The two models are related through a projection on or from the hemisphere model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The Klein disk model is an orthographic projection to the hemisphere model while the Poincaré disk model is a stereographic projection.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] An advantage of the Klein disk model is that lines in this model are Euclidean straight chords.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] A disadvantage is that the Klein disk model is not conformal (circles and angles are distorted).
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] When projecting the same lines in both models on one disk both lines go through the same two ideal points.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] (the ideal points remain on the same spot) also the pole of the chord in the Klein disk model is the center of the circle that contains the arc in the Poincaré disk model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] For ideal points $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ and the formulas become $x=x\ ,\ y=y$ so the points are fixed.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The Poincaré disk model and the Poincaré half-plane model are related by a Möbius transformation.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The Poincaré disk model, as well as the Beltrami–Klein model, are related to the hyperboloid model projectively.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] If we have a point [*t*, *x*1, ..., *x**n*] on the upper sheet of the hyperboloid of the hyperboloid model, thereby defining a point in the hyperboloid model, we may project it onto the hyperplane *t* = 0 by intersecting it with a line drawn through [−1, 0, ..., 0].
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] The result is the corresponding point of the Poincaré disk model.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Compare the formulas for stereographic projection between a sphere and a plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Escher explored the concept of representing infinity on a two-dimensional plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Discussions with Canadian mathematician Harold Scott MacDonald Coxeter around 1956 inspired Escher's interest in hyperbolic tessellations, which are regular tilings of the hyperbolic plane.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] Escher's wood engravings *Circle Limit I–IV* demonstrate this concept between 1958 and 1960, the final one being *Circle Limit IV: Heaven and Hell* in 1960.
[src:non-euclidean-geometry/poincaré-disk-model] According to Bruno Ernst, the best of them is *Circle Limit III*.
